 England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, England","Bradford, Somerset, England":"Bradford, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Peverell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Peverall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peverall","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Old French  <i>Peurel</i> (Latin  <i>Piperellus</i>), a diminutive of Old French  <i>pevre</i> ‘pepper’ (Anglo-Norman French  <i>peivere</i>, Latin  <i>piper</i>), originally perhaps used as a nickname on the Continent but used as a personal name in Anglo-Norman England."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":19,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Peverell III was born in 1436, in Bradford Peverell, Dorset, England, his father, Lord John de Peverell II, was 26 and his mother, Joan de Sampford, was 21. He married Margaret Catherine Montague in 1459, in Bradford, Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1484, in Salisbury, Wiltshire, England, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1436–1484":"1436–1484","1457–1489":"1457–1489","1445–1489":"1445–1489","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1410–1465":"1410–1465","1415–1489":"1415–1489","1459":"1459","1415":"1415","1436":"1436","1435":"1435","1457":"1457","1445":"1445","1489":"1489","1455":"1455","1465":"1465","1410":"1410","1520":"1520","1484":"1484","Bradford Peverell, Dorset, England":"Bradford Peverell, Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bradford Holsworthy, Devon, England":"Bradford, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dorset, Devon, England":"Dorset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Salisbury, Wiltshire, England":"Salisbury, Wiltshire, England","Bradford, Somerset, England":"Bradford, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"1436–1484":"1436–1484","1457–1489":"1457–1489","1445–1489":"1445–1489","1465–1520":"1465–1520","1410–1465":"1410–1465","1415–1489":"1415–1489","1459":"1459","1415":"1415","1436":"1436","1435":"1435","1457":"1457","1445":"1445","1489":"1489